Implementing a conic gradient for creating visually distinct sections within a circular graph is an excellent application of CSS styling. However, the method you're suggesting for inserting text at specific angles directly inside the `::before` pseudo-element's `content` property has limitations. While CSS is powerful for styling, it has its bounds, especially when it comes to positioning text at specific angles or locations outside of a straightforward linear layout.

The `content` property is primarily intended for inserting simple text content or icons directly before or after an element’s content. It's not designed to support detailed layout or positioning of text at multiple, specific angles around a circle. For such detailed positioning, you would typically use additional HTML elements or SVG for greater control.

However, your concept can still be realized with a blend of CSS and HTML or SVG for the text. The CSS provides the circular graph with a conic-gradient background, and either HTML elements (styled and positioned with CSS) or SVG text elements can precisely position the degree texts. Here’s a suggestion on how to achieve the positioning of degree texts:

### Using HTML and CSS:

This solution involves creating additional elements for each degree text and absolutely positioning them around the circle.

```html
<div class="graph">
    <span class="degree" style="top: 0%; left: 50%; transform: translate(-50%, -10%);">360°</span>
    <span class="degree" style="top: 50%; left: 100%; transform: translate(10%, -50%);">90°</span>
    <span class="degree" style="top: 100%; left: 50%; transform: translate(-50%, 10%);">180°</span>
